      {
        "id": 3189703,
        "name": "S_Y\u00e6t\u20acs",
        "username": "Stan_Y",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/stan_y/{size}/77155_2.png",
        "created_at": "2021-06-30T13:27:42.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"171716\">\n<blockquote>\n<p><strong>N.V. Jacques Selosse Initial Champagne</strong>: Disgorged 12th of November 2019. Super-complex with notes of hazelnut cream, tart tatin, preserved lemon, smoke and flint. It is rich, full and powerful, with gentle nuttiness and loads of green apple. There\u2019s a vinous quality and a finish that is chewy and long.</p>\n<p><strong>N.V. Jacques Selosse Champagne Grand Cru Lieux-dits Extra Brut Ay La C\u00f4te Faron</strong>: Disgorged 19th February, 2020. Plenty of brown spice and baked apple to the aroma. There are red fruit and pastry notes too. It is rich and powerful, with all sorts of savoury nuance countering. It is gently frothy and finishes with great drive and energy.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>I am always amazed when people here somehow choose the same thing at the same time.  I had this day before yesterday, same disgorgement, and first Selosse for me.</p>\n<p><strong>N.V. Jacques Selosse Initial Champagne (D\u00e9g. Nov. 2019)</strong>: Have never tried Selosse before and this was stunning. Color is a beautiful light gold, no sign of oxidation. Expressive nose. Vinous, chalky, grippy, medium bodied flavors. This just pops. Special. With my dad wife and son at the beach, glad we brought this.</p>\n<p>Also just had '93 Mugnier Musigny, which unlike the previous bottle from the same case that was slightly past peak, was dark and tannic and mightily youthful.  Very interesting to me how bottles this age follow their own paths.</p>\n<p>Edit: Herwig as we were drinking this I was thinking to myself how much I wish I could afford to drink this as my regular Champagne.  Unlike a lot of experienced folks here I am not usually so particular about which one I drink; for me the bubbles tend to mask nuances.  But this was something else.</p>",
